‘yellow-haired’, pronounced as two syllables. The equivalent term in Ireland is <i>buí</i>, often Anglicized as <i>boy</i>. The surname may also be a shortened form of   Gilboy  .","Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Buadhaigh</b> (see   Bogue  )."]},{"name":"Boyde","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): variant of   Boyd  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Boidh de Boyd was born in 1155, in Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Robert De Longsworth, was 52 and his mother, Eschina De Londoniis of Molle, was 48. He married Lady A FitzAlan in 1223, in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1240, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1155–1240":"1155–1240","1130–1163":"1130–1163","1133–1178":"1133–1178","1183–1263":"1183–1263","1205–1263":"1205–1263","1104–1160":"1104–1160","1107–1186":"1107–1186","1186":"1186","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1163":"1163","1130":"1130","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","1107":"1107","1205":"1205","1104":"1104","1223"